@NODE ARexx
@TITLE "ACE · AREXX interface"
@PREV Main
@NEXT Main


    @{b}AREXX interface @{ub}


    ACE exposes an extended AREXX interface that will allow you to do almost
    everything you want! With the help of REXX, everything is possible,
    everything can be automated! Your creativity will have no limits!

    Here is the list of the available commands on the ACE's AREXX port.

    @{u}Application commands:@{uu}

    @{b}* VERSION@{ub}: Return the ACE version number.

    @{b}* HIDE@{ub}: Iconify ACE.

    @{b}* SHOW@{ub}: Show ACE if it was iconified.

    @{b}* QUIT@{ub}: Quit ACE.

    @{b}* FULLSCREEN ACTIVATE/N,TOGGLE/S@{ub}: Return the full screen status. If @{i}ACTIVATE@{ui}
      is set, @{i}TOGGLE@{ui} is ignored. Setting @{i}ACTIVATE@{ui} at 1 activates the full screen,
      0 go back to the windowed mode. @{i}TOGGLE@{ui} switches the current mode.

    @{b}* ICONIFY ACTIVATE/N,TOGGLE/S@{ub}: Return the full screen status. If @{i}ACTIVATE@{ui}
      is set, @{i}TOGGLE@{ui} is ignored. Setting @{i}ACTIVATE@{ui} at 1 iconifies ACE,
      0 go back to the windowed mode. @{i}TOGGLE@{ui} switches the current mode.

    @{b}* SCREENTOFRONT@{ub}: Put the screen ACE is opened on to front.

    @{b}* SCREENTOBACK@{ub}: Put the screen ACE is opened of to back.

    @{b}* WINDOWTOFRONT@{ub}: Put ACE's main window to front.

    @{b}* WINDOWTOBACK@{ub}: Put ACE's main window to back.

    @{b}* WARNINGS ACTIVATE/N,TOGGLE/S@{ub}: Return or change the warnings display
      preference (warnings are about the DSK or SNA loading).

    @{b}* KEYJOY ACTIVATE/N,TOGGLE/S@{ub}: Return or change the keyboard mapping of
      joystick 0 preference.

    @{u}Emulator commands:@{uu}

    @{b}* RESET HARD/S@{ub}: Reset or reboot the emulator.

    @{b}* PAUSE@{ub}: Pause the emulator.

    @{b}* START STEP/@{ub}: Restart the emulator. If @{i}TYPE@{ui} is specified, only one single
      Z80 instruction will be executed (step by step mode).

    @{b}* CRTC CRTC=TYPE/N@{ub} : If @{i}TYPE@{ui} is specified, select the CRTC type to
      emulate (0 to 4, 3 is Amstrad Plus). If not, return the current emulated
      CRTC type.
      Warning: the Gate Array version might be changed too if it is not
      compatible with the new CRTC type.

    @{b}* GATEARRAY GATEARRAY=VERSION/N@{ub} : If @{i}VERSION@{ui} is specified, select
      the Gate Array version to emulate (40007, 40010, 40226 or 40489, the last
      one is the Amstrad Plus). If not, return the current emulated Gate Array
      version.
      Warning: the CRTC type might be changed too if it is not compatible with
      the new Gate Array version.

    @{b}* WILDSPEED ACTIVATE/N,TOGGLE/S@{ub}: Return or change the wild speed
      preference.

    @{b}* AUDIO=SOUND ACTIVATE/N,TOGGLE/S@{ub}: Return or change the audio preference.

    @{b}* INSERTDISC FILE/A,DRIVE@{ub}: Insert a disc image @{i}FILE@{ui} in to the drive @{i}DRIVE@{ui}
      (0/1 or A/B, drive A is the default one).

    @{b}* EJECTDISC DRIVE@{ub}: Eject the disc image from the drive @{i}DRIVE@{ui}.

    @{b}* GETDISCNAME DRIVE@{ub}: Return the file name of the disc image inserted in the
      drive @{i}DRIVE@{ui}.

    @{b}* INSERTTAPE FILE/A TAP=TAPEAUTOPLAY/S@{ub} : Insert the audio file @{i}FILE@{ui} in the tape
      reader and go to play if @{i}TAPEAUTOPLAY@{ui} is specified.

    @{b}* EJECTTAPE@{ub} : Eject the audio file from the tape reader.

    @{b}* PLAYTAPE@{ub} : Press play on the tape reader.

    @{b}* STOPTAPE@{ub} : Press stop on the tape reader.

    @{b}* GETTAPENAME@{ub} : Return the name of the audio file inserted in the tape reader.

    @{b}* INSERTCARTRIDGE FILE/A FORCE/S@{ub} : Insert a cartridge CPR @{i}FILE@{ui} in the
      cartridge port (Amstrad Plus only). @{i}FORCE@{ui} will switch the ACE in Amstrad
      Plus mode if it was not the case.

    @{b}* EJECTCARTRIDGE@{ub} : Eject the cartridge image file inserted (Amstrad Plus only).

    @{b}* GETCARTRIDGENAME@{ub} : Return the file name of the cartridge image inserted in
      the cartridge port (Amstrad Plus only).

    @{b}* LOADSNA FILE/A@{ub}: Load a snapshot file named @{i}FILE@{ui}.

    @{b}* SAVESNA FILE/A@{ub}: Save a snapshot of the current emulator state into a file
      named @{i}FILE@{ui}.

    @{b}* FLASHROM FILE/A,ROM/A/N@{ub}: Load a file named @{i}FILE@{ui} as an upper ROM number
      @{i}ROM@{ui}.

    @{b}* REMOVEROM ROM/A/N@{ub}: Remove the upper ROM number @{i}ROM@{ui}.

    @{b}* RAWKEYPRESS KEY=CODE/A/N@{ub}: Simulate a key press of the key @{i}CODE@{ui} (being the
      physical key number from the CPC keyboard layout).

    @{b}* RAWKEYRELEASE KEY=CODE/A/N@{ub}: Simulate a key release of the key @{i}CODE@{ui}.

    @{b}* RAWKEYSTROKE KEY=CODE/A/N,DELAY/N@{ub}: Simulate a key press then release of
      the key @{i}CODE@{ui} (physical key number of the CPC keyboard) by waiting a
      @{i}DELAY@{ui} (in microseconds) between the actions. The default @{i}DELAY@{ui} is 19968
      microseconds (one frame), the max value is 1000000 microseconds (one
      second).

    @{b}* KEYBOARDSTROKE STR=STRING/A/F@{ub}: Simulate a full key press and release from
      a string @{i}STRING@{ui}. It is different from @{b}RAWKEYPRESS@{ub}, @{b}RAWKEYRELEASE@{ub} and
      @{b}RAWKEYSTROKE@{ub} because this command depend on the type of keyboard (AZERTY ou QWERTY)
      and the installed firmware ROM is used to perform the translation.

    @{u}Cross-development commands:@{uu}

    @{b}* POKE ADR=ADDRESS/A/N,VAL=VALUE/A/N,LINEAR/S@{ub}: Poke a byte @{i}VALUE@{ui} at the
      address @{i}ADDRESS@{ui} in the emulated CPC memory. If @{i}LINEAR@{ui} is set, the address
      will be considered as linear to the full CPC memory (0x0000-0xFFFF = main
      RAM, 0x10000-0x1FFFF = first 64KB page of the extension RAM, ..).

    @{b}* PEEK ADR=ADDRESS/A/N,LINEAR/S@{ub}: Peek a byte.

    @{b}* LOAD FILE/A,ADR=ADDRESS/N,OFT=OFFSET/N,LEN=LENGTH/N,LINEAR/S,RAW/S@{ub}:
      Load the content @{i}FILE@{ui} from @{i}OFFSET@{ui}, with a maximal @{i}LENGTH@{ui}, at @{i}ADDRESS@{ui}. If
      RAW is set, then any binary header will be ignored. @{i}ADDRESS@{ui} is mandatory
      if no header is present.

    @{b}* SAVE FILE/A,ADR=ADDRESS/A/N,LEN=LENGTH/A/N,EXE=EXECUTION/N,LINEAR/S,RAW/S@{ub}:
      Save a part of the CPC memory into a @{i}FILE@{ui}.

    @{b}* OUT PORT/A/N,VAL=VALUE/A/N@{ub}: Put a byte @{i}VALUE@{ui} on the CPC port address
      @{i}PORT@{ui}.

    @{b}* INP PORT/A/N @{ub}: Read a byte from the CPC port address @{i}PORT@{ui}.

    @{b}* BREAKPOINTS ACTIVATE/N,TOGGLE/S@{ub}: Return or set the breakpoints
      preference.

    @{b}* SETBREAKCONDITIONS VBL/S,HBL/S,OPCODE/S,INT=INTERRUPT/S,DISC=DISCACCESS/S,@{ub}
      @{b}BADVBL/S,BADHBL/S@{ub}: Set or unset a break condition.

    @{b}* ADDBREAKPOINT TYPE/A,ADR=ADDRESS/A/N,ADRMASK=ADDRESSMASK/N,ACCESS,@{ub}
      @{b}VAL=VALUE/N,VALMASK=VALUEMASK/N,CONDITION,STEP/N,NAME,WATCHER/S@{ub}: Set a
      breakpoint of type @{i}TYPE@{ui} (EXECUTE, MEMORY ou PORTS) named @{i}NAME@{ui} for an
      access @{i}ACCESS@{ui} (READ-ONLY, WRITE-ONLY ou READ-WRITE), at the address
      @{i}ADDRESS@{ui}, depending on a mask @{i}ADDRESSMASK@{ui}, for a value @{i}VALUE@{ui} with a mask
      @{i}VALUEMASK@{ui} every @{i}STEP@{ui} under the condition @{i}CONDITION@{ui}.
      @{u}Note 1:@{uu} If @{i}WATCHER@{ui} is specified the breakpoint will not stop and will just
      update the match count.
      @{u}Note 2:@{uu} If a breakpoint with the same options exists, then the
      @{i}CONDITION@{ui}, @{i}STEP@{ui}, @{i}NAME@{ui} and mode (@{i}WATCHER@{ui}) are updated.
      @{u}Note 3:@{uu} Value and mask are ignored  for execution breakpoints.
      @{u}Note 4;@{uu} Default address mask value is 0xFFFF (it means "exact match").
      @{u}Note 5:@{uu} Default value mask is 0x00 (it mean "any value match").

    @{b}* REMOVEBREAKPOINT TYPE/A,ADR=ADDRESS/N,ADRMASK=ADDRESSMASK/N,ACCESS,
      VAL=VALUE/N,VALMASK=VALUEMASK/N,ALL/S@{ub}: Remove a breakpoint of type
      @{i}TYPE@{ui} (EXECUTE, MEMORY or PORTS) for an access @{i}ACCESS@{ui} (READ-ONLY, WRITE-ONLY
      or READ-WRITE), at the address @{i}ADDRESS@{ui}, with a mask @{i}ADDRESSMASK@{ui}, for a
      value @{i}VALUE@{ui} using a mask @{i}VALUEMASK@{ui}. If @{i}ALL@{ui} is specified then
      all the breakpoints of type @{i}TYPE@{ui} are deleted (other parameters are then
      ignored).

    @{b}* AF VAL=VALUE/N@{ub}: Get or set the AF register of the Z80.
    @{b}* BC VAL=VALUE/N@{ub}: See @{b}AF@{ub}.
    @{b}* DE VAL=VALUE/N@{ub}: See @{b}AF@{ub}.
    @{b}* HL VAL=VALUE/N@{ub}: See @{b}AF@{ub}.
    @{b}* SP VAL=VALUE/N@{ub}: See @{b}AF@{ub}.
    @{b}* PC VAL=VALUE/N@{ub}: See @{b}AF@{ub}.
    @{b}* AFx VAL=VALUE/N@{ub}: Secondary register; see @{b}AF@{ub}.
    @{b}* BCx VAL=VALUE/N@{ub}: Secondary register; see @{b}AF@{ub}.
    @{b}* DEx VAL=VALUE/N@{ub}: Secondary register; see @{b}AF@{ub}.
    @{b}* HLx VAL=VALUE/N@{ub}: Secondary register; see @{b}AF@{ub}.
    @{b}* IX VAL=VALUE/N@{ub}: See @{b}AF@{ub}.
    @{b}* IY VAL=VALUE/N@{ub}: See @{b}AF@{ub}.
    @{b}* I VAL=VALUE/N@{ub}: 8 bit register; see @{b}AF@{ub}.

    @{b}* GETUSERCOUNTER TYPE/A@{ub} : return the current value of the user counter of
      type @{i}TYPE@{ui}.
      Theses counters counters are associated to the ones from the @{"Z80 window" link Z80Window } and the
      possible values are:
        . MICROSECONDS for the microseconds counter.
        . LINES for the line counter.
        . FRAMES for the frame counter.

    @{b}* RESETUSERCOUNTER TYPE/A@{ub} : reset remet the user counter specified with
      @{i}TYPE@{ui}.
      The possible values are the same than from @{b}GETUSERCOUNTER@{ub}.

    @{b}* GETLASTBREAKTYPE@{ub} : return the status for the last activated
      breakpoint(s). This option is very useful inside scripts executed at
      breakpoints activation because it allows you to know in which conditions
      the break occurred. The status is returned in the form of a string formated
      as followed:

      [Execution][I/O Port][Memory][Interrupt][HBL][VBL][Bad HBL][Bad VBL][Disc access][Step by step][On screen break]

      Each section under brackets is related to a type of breakpoint and will
      contain "-" if the associated type of breakpoint was not active during the
      last break. If it was active, then the related section will contain its
      name if it was named or a string with the name of the type of breakpoint
      if it was not.

    @{b}* ONSCREENBREAK X/A/N,Y/A/N@{ub} : set a breakpoint for the display position
      @{i}X@{ui},@{i}Y@{ui}. This position are related to the video frame fly
      and do not depend of graphic resolution.
      @{u}Note:@{uu} this breakpoint is related to the breakpoint "Break on the
      mouse clicked position" available from the "Monitoring" menu and only one
      can be set at once.

@ENDNODE

@NODE TapeToHDWrapper
@TITLE "ACE · Tape to hard disc wrapper"
@PREV Main
@NEXT Main


    @{b}Tape to hard disc wrapper@{ub}


    ACE allows you to share a directory from your hard disc with the emulated
    CPC through the tape interface. With this feature you can read and write
    files of a directory of your choice . Loading operations are in full speed
    (from the CPC point of view the files are loaded/saved with no delay), you
    can use long file names up to 16 characters (firmware maximum limit), and
    you have access to subdirectories.

    @{u}Configuring the wrapper:@{uu}

    Once the option "Tape to hard disk wrapper" activated from the ACE
    configuration menu, you then have access to the shared directory through
    the tape interface. You can also use the tooltype TAPE2HD to activate the
    wrapper by default.

    If a disk ROM is installed (which is generally the case) you have to use
    the command "|TAPE" to use the tape interface (the "|DISC" command switches
    back to the disc interface). Once done, all the file operation commands
    (CAT, LOAD, SAVE, OPENIN, OPENOUT...) will grant you access to the shared
    directory of you hard disc.

    This directory defaults to "PROGDIR:Share/" but you can change it by using
    the TAPE2HDPATH tooltype. For security reasons it is not possible to access
    to files outside this directory (except the ones from subdirectories).
    Moreover only files compatibles with the 16 characters file name limit are
    visible (the others are hidden and a message inform you about their
    existence).

    @{u}Using the wrapper:@{uu}

    The CAT command which lists the files might display a lot of entries if your
    directory is full of stuff. The scrolling could then prevent you from
    reading the first files of the list. To solve this issue, you can use the
    [CONTROL] key to hold the catalog display. Also, you can press [ESC] to
    simply cancel the catalog listing at any time.

    Moreover, the catalog is displayed in a detailed way much more useful than
    the AMSDOS defaults.

    Here is an example:

    @{b}@{fg fill}[HOME]@{fg text}@{ub}
    @{b}@{fg fill}Favorite Games/  [DIR]                 |@{fg text}@{ub}
    @{b}@{fg fill}Favorite Demos/  [DIR]                 |@{fg text}@{ub}
    @{b}@{fg fill}Menu.bas         11938 B$0170 0000 2E22|@{fg text}@{ub}
    @{b}@{fg fill}Music.bin         4055 B&6380 4000 0480|@{fg text}@{ub}
    @{b}@{fg fill}Music.wav            4MB*Data          |@{fg text}@{ub}
    @{b}@{fg fill}Readme.txt        3456 B*ASCII         |@{fg text}@{ub}

    And how to understand it:

    @{b}*@{ub} The first line displays under brackets the name of the current
    directory; HOME indicates the root of the shared directory.
    @{b}*@{ub} The keyword [DIR] indicated a directory entry.
    @{b}*@{ub} The size of the files is displayed in bytes (B), kilobytes (KB),
      megabytes (MB) and even gigabytes (GB) depending on their size.
    @{b}*@{ub} The type of the files is displayed using the common firmware flags:
        $ For a BASIC file.
        & For a binary file.
        % For a protected file.
        * For a non-system file (ASCII or raw data).

    Finally, you have to know that the CPC operating system does not allow
    directory browsing ; no command exists for such operation. To access to the
    directories using the hard disc wrapper, you simply have to use the "OPENIN"
    command with the name of the directory to enter followed by a "/" sign
    (anyway, directories are always displayed with this trailing slash in the
    catalog). Please note that the directory names are then limited to 15
    characters instead of 16. To go back to the parent directory, you just have
    to use OPENIN"/", while OPENIN":" will put you directly into the root shared
    directory (jut like in AmigaShell through the CD command).

    During file opening in reading mode, in order to be more compliant with
    existing programs, the file extensions management defaults in the same way
    the AMSDOS does. If a file name is less than 8 characters long, reading
    attempts will be done with pending ".", ".bas" then ".bin" extensions.

    During file opening in write mode, no default extension management is done.
    (like for the original tape interface).

    @{u}Technical details:@{uu}

    From a technical point of view, this wrapper is implemented with the help
    of a modified firmware ROM and an Z80 illegal instruction. When the tape to
    hard disc wrapper is disabled, the emulation is not altered at all. Once
    activated, he firmware ROM is patched on the fly to make use of the special
    illegal instruction. Then, every time the Z80 emulation encounters this
    instruction during the firmware ROM code execution, the wrapper specific
    functions are engaged.

    @{i}@{fg shine}Warning: the wrapper will not work if you do not use of the official@{fg text}@{ui}
    @{i}@{fg shine}Amstrad firmware ROM version (all of them are compatibles).@{fg text}@{ui}

@ENDNODE

